In Uganda, Caritas Denmark has worked with five local partners since 2001 with MFA funding. The engagement during 2018-2021 amounts to DKK 36.8 million and will enhance sustainable rural development, through strengthening farmersâ associations and advocacy at national level. This will be facilitated through a network of Ugandan CBOs/NGOs, led by Caritas Uganda, supported by Caritas Denmark. In the years to come, with a humanitarian-development nexus approach more emphasis will be placed on climate change mitigation to reduce the effect on rural livelihoods and threat to the development of farmers associations. Interventions will strengthen the resilience of local communities in cooperation with relevant local authorities, including ensuring the participation of civil society in local development planning. The growing number of unemployed youth is a cause for concern in Uganda, as they tend to migrate to the urban city centres where they become part of the growing number of urban poor. Caritas Denmark and partners will apply innovative ways of including youth in economic development based on previous pilot activities and evidence-based information gathered from target group feedback. The retention of youth in rural areas is key for the labour intensive sustainable agricultural practices required to adapt to the changing climate.

top.value: Caritas Denmarkâs support to India is geographically focused to the isolated region of North East India, bordering Myanmar, China, Bhutan and Bangladesh. Caritas Denmark has worked with five partners in this region since 1999. The programme has been one of Caritas Denmarkâs most successful, where in 2015 the target groups managed to fundraise more funds locally than those received from Caritas Denmark. An exit strategy for the end of 2018 has therefore been underway over the past three years. The programme will be consolidated with a 2018 budget of DKK 1.8 million. The programme has demonstrated positive impact in improving the livelihoods of the rural farmers in North East India and the programme is assessed to be sustainable. Funds for the on-going activities are secured by tapping into Indian government development funds. The focus of the exit phase is to consolidate the already-made changes, especially those of the federations, which are key to support self-help groups in gaining sustainability. These self-help groups have been supported to start up community loan groups and strengthen the marketing of their agricultural produce. This is done through value-chain activities and the establishment of a marketing association, serving farmers in the region. At the same time, the farmers have received training in business development to allow them to access both the national market as well as the international market.

In Myanmar, Caritas Denmark works with the local partner Karuna Mission Social Solidarity (KMSS â Caritas Myanmar) to promote sustainable agricultural development, strengthening of civil society at the community level, through organisation and training of community groups alongside advocacy promoting the rights of poor agricultural communities. During 2018-2021 Caritas Denmark will continue to work in seven areas where programme activities have been implemented since 2005, with a four-year budget of DKK 20 million. The focus during 2018-21 is to strengthen the human rights-based approach in the programme. The aim is to address issues that are affecting the rural poor farmers and their livelihood. Furthermore, Caritas Denmark will take a nexus approach in programme planning and implementation to address climate change via disaster risk reduction and climate change adaptation measures as most farmersâ livelihoods are affected by changes in seasonal weather patterns and natural disasters. Caritas Denmark will work together with CAFOD in Myanmar in a strategic partnership to enhance locally led humanitarian response capacity.

Overall objective of the country programme 2022-25:
Strengthen the resilience, social cohesion and living conditions of the populations in Uganda 
confronted with the effects of the multifaceted crisis by enhancing sustainable food production, 
increased income, and their capacity to act as change agents of own and community welfare.

The long-term changes (outcomes) of the country engagement 2022-2025:
1. Farmer cooperatives, local partners and national advocacy platforms are voicing interests of 
small-scale farmers, refugees, and youths on issues of relevance to them, including climate 
change adaptation, land rights and access of women and refugees, youth employment and 
easy market certification of value-added produce
2. Small-scale farmers have increased sustainable production and sale of produce through 
organised farming and climate smart techniques
3. Increased access and use of innovative green technology solutions reducing deforestation and 
wood fuel dependence among refugee, host, and vulnerable households
4. Youth and women are empowered and have gained increased influence through leadership 
positions, school peace clubs, the national youth-led advocacy platform (NYAP) and 
promotion of gender equity
5. All direct local partners (incl. at diocesan level) comply with CIMS and /or CHS
6. Local partners take lead and have increased influence at the international sphere

Building on its long-standing partnership with Caritas Jordan and in line with the rolling three-year Jordan Response Plan spearheaded and coordinated by the Government of Jordan, Caritas Denmark will continue to address the needs of vulnerable Syrian refugees and Jordanians with a four-year budget of DKK 26.5 million. This will include ensuring access to, and provision of, health care services through Caritas Jordanâs primary health care centres and referrals to partner hospitals and facilities. Caritas will continue to provide pre- and post-natal health care services, support and information to expectant mothers to ensure a healthy pregnancy, labour and delivery for mother and child. Caritas Jordan will also continue to inform and support patients at risk of, or with non-communicable diseases (NCDs), such as diabetes, cardiovascular diseases and chronic respiratory diseases, thereby reducing the risk of premature death, secondary disease complications and/or disabilities, and through this enhancing patient prospects for employment opportunities.
